tx-swr32: Dark Flaring Analysis
================================

Identifies unpermitted ("dark") flaring in the Permian Basin by
cross-referencing three public datasets:

  1. SWR 32 exception permits — scraped from the Texas RRC
  2. RRC well locations — parsed from EBCDIC bulk data files
  3. VIIRS Nightfire — satellite-detected flares from EOG/NOAA

The pipeline spatially matches satellite flare detections to nearby
wells, then checks whether those wells had valid SWR 32 flaring
permits at the time of detection.

Current results: 87 flare sites with 6,021 detection-days across
2012-2026, none covered by an SWR 32 exception permit.


Setup
-----
Requires: uv, duckdb CLI, Playwright (chromium)
Optional: EOG account for VNF data (credentials in .env)

  uv sync
  uv run playwright install chromium
  make db


Operator linkage
-----------------
Each well now carries an operator_no extracted from the EBCDIC type 01
root record (bytes 28-33). The analysis joins directly:

  wells.operator_no -> operators.operator_number -> operator_name

29% of dark flare detection-days resolve to a named operator via the
current P-5 file. The remainder show as "OP#NNNNNN" — these are
operator numbers for companies no longer in the active P-5 roster.

Next steps
----------
- Enrich operator coverage: historical P-5 files, or scrape the RRC
  operator lookup by number to fill in names for inactive operators.
- Aggregate by operator: rank operators by total dark flaring activity.
